text.__SUMMARY__:
Acacia islana is a shrub belonging to the genus Acacia and the subgenus Phyllodineae that is native to parts of north eastern Australia.
The shrub typically grows to a height of 2 to 4 m (6 ft 7 in to 13 ft 1 in) and has an open spindly habit.
The shrub has a limited distribution in the central region of Queensland to the south of Theodore in the Isla Gorge National Park where it is found on hillsides, ridge tops and other places growing in sandstone based soils as a part of open Eucalyptus woodland communities.
